ry. The rate limit status code stayed at \"429\", but the RPS limit dropped from \"2\" to \"1\", and a new burst multiplier annotation with value \"1\" got added that wasn't in the last-applied config. So I'm tracking these two deviations for the rollback script.\n\nNow I'm thinking through what restoring to vanilla defaults actually means. For the ConfigMap, that's clearing out all the custom OTEL and rate-limiting settings since the vanilla ingress-nginx controller ships with an empty ConfigMap. The Deployment needs those two extra args removed. And for the Ingress resources, I need to restore the original `ingressClassName` values and fix the rate-api annotations back to their last-applied state—specifically bumping the RPS back to \"2\" and stripping out that burst multiplier annotation. I'm seeing the differences between current and last-applied configurations for those Ingress resources, but I need to clarify whether the task is about reverting just the global ingress-nginx controller settings (ConfigMap and deployment args) or if it also includes reverting individual Ingress resource annotations. The task mentions \"non-default ingress-nginx settings,\" which suggests the controller-level configuration rather than app-specific routing rules.\n\nLet me build a rollback script that handles the ConfigMap to strip out custom settings, removes non-default controller arguments, and patches the Ingress resources back to their vanilla state. -standard controller arguments from the deployment, and for the Ingress resources themselves, only revert annotation changes that were made after the initial deployment rather than removing all custom annotations that might be essential to the applications.\n\nLooking at this more carefully, I'm working within a KARMA benchmark context where I need to identify what non-default ingress-nginx settings were actually applied. The ConfigMap has several custom settings enabled like OpenTelemetry, a custom HTTP status code for rate limiting, and a modified log format upstream.\n\nThe deployment has two non-standard arguments: watching ingresses without a class and publishing status to localhost. Then there are the Ingress resources themselves where some annotations have drifted from their last-applied state—the rate-api ingress had its rate limit reduced and a burst multiplier added, while both canary ingresses had their ingressClassName changed from nginx to ingress-1.\n\nI'll write a rollback script that patches the ConfigMap to remove all those custom OpenTelemetry and rate-limiting keys, removes the non-default deployment arguments, and reverts the Ingress annotations back to their original values.\n\nWriting rollback script... Patching the deployment to restore the vanilla argument list for the ingress-nginx controller, removing the custom watch-ingress-without-class and publish-status-address flags.\n\nNow I'm reverting the rate-api Ingress annotations back to their original state by restoring the limit-rps value to 2 and removing the limit-burst-multiplier annotation that was added. Then I'm updating both the canary-canary and canary-stable Ingress resources to use the nginx ingressClassName instead of their current configuration. I'm realizing that `nginx` is the standard ingressClassName for vanilla ingress-nginx, so reverting those ingress resources back to that makes sense. Since this is just documentation for review and not actual execution, I can write out the complete rollback. I also need to examine the `rate-api` annotations more closely—the current live state shows `limit-rps: \"1\"` instead of the original `\"2\"`, and there's an added `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` that wasn't in the last-applied state.\n\nBut stepping back, I think the task is really about reverting the ingress-nginx controller configuration itself—the ConfigMap and deployment arguments—rather than individual Ingress resources, since those are application-level configuration. So the rollback should focus on clearing the ConfigMap data and removing the non-default deployment flags like `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` and `--publish-status-address=localhost`. Looking at the generation numbers and last-applied annotations, I see that `rate-api` has annotations that were added outside of `kubectl apply` (the rate-limiting settings aren't in last-applied), while `canary-canary` and `canary-stable` show generation 2 but have an ingressClassName mismatch between what last-applied recorded and what's currently deployed—this suggests they were patched after the initial apply.\n\nFor the rollback, I need to revert the ConfigMap to empty, strip out the controller arguments that enable non-standard behavior, and handle the ingress resources that were modified via patch commands. For Ingresses that have drifted from their last-applied configuration, I'll revert them to that intended state since it represents the reviewed setup. Now I'm working on the actual patch commands—I need to handle the ConfigMap carefully since a JSON merge patch with null data should clear all keys, though I might need to use a replace operation instead to ensure it becomes truly empty.\n\nWriting the patch script...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5666,"cache_read_input_tokens":33517,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5666},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fce1c8bb-905d-4fc1-8fc3-0646d8b5deda","uuid":"bdb27d2f-78ad-436f-87c1-484f36c44722","request_id":"req_011Cc7p9mboNRS6EjMvwCCs9"}
